"What should I get for you?" Ivory asked the silent princess, whose pigtails swung back and forth with her vigorous knocking. "Yes?" Ivory whispered, chuckling softly. The usually closed-off princess showed such enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! See you later?" Ivory asked, stood up, and weaved her way through the chaos of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like Malfarben.
Ivory ran through the hallways and tried to ignore the murmurs of the maids.
"I've heard that she is possessed by Queen Eirwen and therefore keeps returning to this room."
"I have heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal?"
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the gossip, and continued walking. The royal painter's studio was located in the east wing behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six Urdragons supposedly created by Frostfall. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual chaos. Splashes of paint everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different sight greeted her. The entire room was clean, and in front of a red velvet backdrop stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being portrayed in a portrait.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is being portrayed?" Aquilo asked and winked at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, ignoring him largely and gathering the things the quiet princess desired. "I'm only here to get some art supplies."
"Little girl, do you want to go already?" asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I but not." Ivory found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Moreover, I am not a girl."
"The prince, however, had a different opinion. 'Oh sweetie, this is just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!,' he said indistinctly."
"I have to go," said Ivory, feeling uncomfortable with the prince's response. At that moment, all the ugly comments he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back to her. I just want to leave here.
"Are you leaving already?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That is no behavior for a future king!" Ivory said.
"No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life means anything to him." He glanced at the painter briefly before leaning closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed multiple times in the past, but never by a prince, let alone the crown prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'no' means?" Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away from her.
"No," Aquilo answered with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he wants, does not know what the word "no" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He threw back his hair, which whipped around in the cold air.
"Now get it through your head! Why me? I'm a threat to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo raised Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
